\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Sheaves and Locally Ringed Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset toc
LatexCommand tableofcontents

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Presheaves and Sheaves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Presheaves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
presheaf 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 on a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 assigns to each open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 a set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

, and to every pair of nested open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{res}_{U}^{V}:\mathcal{F}(V)\to\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

, called the 
\series bold
restriction map
\series default
, such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(\emptyset)=0$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\text{res}_{U}^{U}$
\end_inset

 is the identity map for all open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\text{res}_{U}^{V}\circ\text{res}_{V}^{W}=\text{res}_{U}^{W}$
\end_inset

 for all open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset V\subset W$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
sections
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

; elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(X)$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
global sections
\series default
.
 The restriction maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{res}_{U}^{V}$
\end_inset

 are written as 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mapsto f|_{U}$.

\end_inset

 Very often we will also write 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(U,\mathcal{F})$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Morphism of Presheaves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{2}$
\end_inset

 be presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\series bold
morphism of presheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\mathcal{F}_{1}\to\mathcal{F}_{2}$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is a family of maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}:\mathcal{F}_{1}(U)\to\mathcal{F}_{2}(U)$
\end_inset

 for all open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that for all pairs of open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, the following diagram commutes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
mathcal{F}_1 (V) 
\backslash
arrow[r, " 
\backslash
varphi _{_V} "] 
\backslash
arrow[d, " 
\backslash
text{res} ^V _U ", swap ] & 
\backslash
mathcal{F} _2 (V) 
\backslash
arrow[d, " 
\backslash
text{res} ^V _U "]  
\backslash

\backslash
  
\backslash
mathcal{F}_2 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi _{_U} ", swap]  & 
\backslash
mathcal{F}_2 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Composition of morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 of presheaves is defined in the obvious way: 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\circ\psi:=(\varphi_{U}\circ\psi_{U})_{U}$
\end_inset

.
 We obtain the category 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Psh}(X)$
\end_inset

 of presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Category Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the language of category theory, we can define presheaves in a very
 concise way.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space.
 We denote by 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{O}(X)$
\end_inset

 
\series default
to be the category whose objects are open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and whose morphisms are inclusion maps.
 Then a presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is just a contravariant functor from
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{O}(X)$
\end_inset

 
\series default
to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Set}$
\end_inset

, and morphisms of presheaves are natural transformations between functors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We can also replace the category 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Set}$
\end_inset

 with any other category 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 to obtain the notion of a presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 with values in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

.
 This signifies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 is an object in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 for every open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and that the restriction maps are morphisms in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sheaves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Presheaves on a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are top-down constructions; we can restrict information from larger to
 smaller sets.
 However, many objects in mathematics are bottom-up constructions; they
 are defined locally, which we then piece together to obtain something global.
 Presheaves do not provide the means to deduce global properties from the
 properties we find locally in the open sets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 This is where the idea of sheaves come in.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{sheaf}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 which satisfies the following 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{sheaf axiom}$
\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 is an open covering of an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and suppose that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 a section 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}\in\mathcal{F}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 is given such that for each pair 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i_{1}}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i_{2}}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\in\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i_{1}}|_{U_{i_{1}}\cap U_{i_{2}}}=s_{i_{2}}|_{U_{i_{1}}\cap U_{i_{2}}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists a unique section 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{U_{i}}=s_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
morphism of sheaves 
\series default
is a morphism of presheaves.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Sh}(X)$
\end_inset

 to be the full subcategory of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Psh}(X)$
\end_inset

, whose objects are sheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and morphisms being natural transformations.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 be open, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}\in\mathcal{F}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}|_{U_{ij}}=s_{j}|_{U_{ij}}$
\end_inset

.
 By the sheaf condition, there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{U_{i}}=s_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $s,s'\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{U_{i}}=s'|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $s=s'$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we can think of sections 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 as being a collection of compatible sections 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}\in\mathcal{F}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 (compatible meaning 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}|_{U_{ij}}=s_{j}|_{U_{ij}}$
\end_inset

).
 More formally, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}(U)=\left\{ (s_{i})_{i}\in\prod_{i}\mathcal{F}(U_{i})\mid s_{i}|_{U_{ij}}=s_{j}|_{U_{ij}}\text{ for all }i,j\in I.\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The sheaf axioms imply that any sheaf has exactly one section of the empty
 set.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The empty set 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

 can be written as the union of an empty family (that is, the indexing set
 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

).
 The condition given for the sheaf property is vacuously true.
 So there must exist a unique section in 
\begin_inset Formula $F(\emptyset)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be a set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf of functions on a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with values in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 The only thing preventing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 from being a sheaf is the 
\emph on
existence 
\emph default
of global functions since 
\emph on
uniqueness 
\emph default
is already guarenteed.
 Indeed, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 is an open covering of an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and suppose that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}\in\mathcal{F}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}|_{U_{ij}}=f_{j}|_{U_{ij}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Then if 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U_{i}}=f_{i}=g|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, then we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $f=g$
\end_inset

.
 This is because 
\begin_inset Formula $f=g$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=g(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, and this is true since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U_{i(x)}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i(x)\in I$
\end_inset

 (depending on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

), hence 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=f_{i(x)}(x)=g(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Reformulating the sheaf axiom
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We give a reformulation of the sheaf axiom in terms of arrows.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open set in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 We define maps 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\rho:\mathcal{F}(U)\to\prod_{i\in I}\mathcal{F}(U_{i}), &  & s\mapsto(s|_{U_{i}})_{i}\\
\sigma:\prod_{i\in I}\mathcal{F}(U_{i})\to\prod_{(i,j)\in I\times I}\mathcal{F}(U_{i}\cap U_{j}), &  & (s_{i})_{i}\mapsto(s_{i}|_{U_{i}\cap U_{j}})_{(i,j)}\\
\sigma':\prod_{i\in I}\mathcal{F}(U_{i})\to\prod_{(i,j)\in I\times I}\mathcal{F}(U_{i}\cap U_{j}), &  & (s_{i})_{i}\mapsto(s_{j}|_{U_{i}\cap U_{j}})_{(i,j)}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf, if it satisfies for all 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and all open coverings 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 the following condition: The diagram
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
mathcal{F}(U) 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
rho "] & 
\backslash
displaystyle
\backslash
prod _{i 
\backslash
in I} 
\backslash
mathcal{F}(U_i )  
\backslash
arrow[r, " 
\backslash
sigma ", shift left = 1] 
\backslash
arrow[r, " 
\backslash
sigma ' ", shift right = 1 , swap]  & 
\backslash
displaystyle
\backslash
prod _{(i , j) 
\backslash
in I 
\backslash
times I } 
\backslash
mathcal{F}(U_i 
\backslash
cap U_j ) 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is exact.
 This means that the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is injective and that its image is the set of elements 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{i})_{i}\in\prod_{i\in I}\mathcal{F}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma((s_{i})_{i})=\sigma'((s_{i})_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For presheaves of abelian groups (or with values in any abelian category)
 we can reformulate the definition of a sheaf as follows: A presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf if and only if for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and all coverings 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 the sequence of abelian groups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[column sep=huge, row sep=0.4, ampersand replacement=
\backslash
&] 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

0 
\backslash
arrow[r] 
\backslash
