begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be a set.
 For each open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U):=E$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf (whose restriction maps being the identity map) called the 
\series bold
constant sheaf with value 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sheaves are determined by their values on a basis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 be a basis of the topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 If we know the value 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 of a sheaf on every element 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

, then we can use the sheaf property to determine 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(V)$
\end_inset

 on an arbitrary open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We simply cover 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 by elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
 Here is a more systematic way of saying this:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{F}(V) & =\left\{ (s_{U})_{U}\in\prod_{\substack{U\in\mathcal{B}\\
U\subseteq V
}
}\mathcal{F}(U)\mid\text{for }U'\subseteq U\text{ both in }\mathcal{B}\text{ we have }s_{U}|_{U'}=s_{U'}\right\} \nonumber \\
 & =\lim_{\substack{U\in\mathcal{B}\\
U\subseteq V
}
}\mathcal{F}(U).\label{eq:sheafdefinedonbasis}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Using this observation, we see that it suffices to define a sheaf on a basis
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 of open sets of the topology of a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

: Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 as a full subcategory of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{O}(X)$
\end_inset

, then a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 is a contravariant functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}:\mathcal{B}\to\mathbf{Set}$
\end_inset

.
 Every such presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 can be extended to a presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}'$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by using 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:sheafdefinedonbasis})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as a definition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be the presheaf of bounded continuous functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 with values in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is not a sheaf.
 Indeed, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}=(i,i+2)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}=x\mid_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 is a covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and there is no bounded continuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mid_{U_{i}}=f_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 The sheafification of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{\mathbb{R};\mathbb{R}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gluing Sheaves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{i}$
\end_inset

 be a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Assume that for each pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)$
\end_inset

 of indices we are given isomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{ij}:\mathcal{F}_{j}|_{U_{ij}}\to\mathcal{F}_{i}|_{U_{ij}}$
\end_inset

 satisfying for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j,k\in I$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cocycle condition
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{ik}=\varphi_{ij}\circ\varphi_{jk}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{ijk}$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists a sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 isomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}:\mathcal{F}_{i}\to\mathcal{F}|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}\circ\varphi_{ij}=\psi_{j}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{ij}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}$
\end_inset

 are uniquely determined up to unique isomorphism by these conditions.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 to be the set of collections of sections which are locally compatible:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}(U)=\left\{ (s_{i})_{i\in I}\in\prod_{i\in I}\mathcal{F}_{i}(U_{i}\cap U)\mid s_{i}|_{U_{ij}\cap U}=\varphi_{ij}(s_{j})|_{U_{ij}\cap U}\text{ for all }i,j\in I.\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The restriction maps are defined pointwise (i.e.
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{i})_{i\in I}|_{V}=(s_{i}|_{U_{i}\cap V}){}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

).
 The cocycle ensures that this definition makes sense.
 Let us verify that this is indeed a sheaf.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 By relabeling if neccessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}=U_{i}\cap U$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i'}\}_{i'\in I'}$
\end_inset

 be an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{ii'})_{i\in I}\in\mathcal{F}(U{}_{i'})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{ii'})_{i\in I}|_{U_{ii'j'}}=(s_{ij'})_{i\in I}|_{U_{ij'i'}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i',j'\in I'$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{ii'}\in\mathcal{F}_{i}(U_{ii'})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i'\in I'$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{ii'}|_{U_{ii'j}}=\varphi_{ij}(s_{ji'})|_{U_{ji'i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i'\in I'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{ii'}|_{U_{ii'j'}}=s_{ij'}|_{U_{ij'i'}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i',j'\in I'$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For each 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{ii'}\}_{i'\in I'}$
\end_inset

 is a cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{ii'}|_{U_{ii'j'}}=s_{ij'}|_{U_{ij'i'}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i',j'\in I'$
\end_inset

 , there exists a unique element 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}\in\mathcal{F}_{i}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}|_{U_{ii'}}=s_{ii'}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i'\in I$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{i})_{i\in I}\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 It suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}|_{U_{ij}}=\varphi_{ij}(s_{j})|_{U_{ij}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{iji'}\}_{i'\in I'}$
\end_inset

 is a cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{ij}$
\end_inset

, and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
s_{i}|_{U_{iji'}} & =s_{ii'}|_{U_{iji'}}\\
 & =\varphi_{ij}(s_{ji'})|_{U_{iji'}}\\
 & =\varphi_{ij}(s_{ji'}|_{U_{iji'}})\\
 & =\varphi_{ij}(s_{j}|_{U_{iji'}})\\
 & =\varphi_{ij}(s_{j})|_{U_{iji'}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i'\in I'$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}|_{U_{ij}}=\varphi_{ij}(s_{j})|_{U_{ij}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now fix 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 We define the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}:\mathcal{F}_{i}\to\mathcal{F}|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Then for 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}_{i}(U)$
\end_inset

, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}(s)=(\varphi_{ji}(s|_{U_{j}\cap U}))_{j\in I}$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{j})_{j\in I}\in\mathcal{F}|_{U_{i}}(U)$
\end_inset

, then we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}^{-1}((s_{j})_{j\in I})=s_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 It is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a bijection with inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, if 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}(s|_{V})=\psi_{i}(s)|_{V}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism of sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}:\mathcal{F}_{i}\to\mathcal{F}|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 We repeat this construction for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 to get an isomorpism 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}:\mathcal{F}_{i}\to\mathcal{F}|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}\circ\varphi_{ij}=\psi_{j}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{ij}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

 follows from a direct calculation: for 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}_{j}(U_{ij})$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\psi_{i}\circ\varphi_{ij})(s) & =\psi_{i}(\varphi_{ij}(s))\\
 & =(\varphi_{ki}(\varphi_{ij}(s)|_{U_{ijk}}))_{k\in I}\\
 & =(\varphi_{ki}(\varphi_{ij}(s))|_{U_{ijk}}){}_{k\in I}\\
 & =(\varphi_{kj}(s)|_{U_{ijk}})_{k\in I}\\
 & =(\varphi_{kj}(s|_{U_{ijk}}))_{k\in I}\\
 & =\psi_{j}(s).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Stalks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, there exists a smallest neighborhood containing 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can determine the sheaf completely by computing the values of the
 sheaf on these open sets.
 The problem of course is that the limit of the diagram which consists of
 all open neighborhoods of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 may not exist, i.e.
 we may not have a smallest open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 However, colimits do exist in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Set}$
\end_inset

, and there's nothing stopping us from looking at colimits in the diagram
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

-images of neighborhoods of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, considered as a contravariant functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}:\mathbf{O}(X)\to\mathbf{Set}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 be a point.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{U}(x):=\{U\subseteq X\mid U\text{ is an open neighborhood of }x\}
\]

\end_inset

be the set of open neighborhoods of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, ordered by inclusion.
 We consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{U}(x)$
\end_inset

 as a full subcategory of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{O}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 By restricting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{O}(x)$
\end_inset

, we obtain a contravariant functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}:\mathbf{U}(x)\to\mathbf{Set}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the category 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{U}(x)$
\end_inset

 is filtered: for any two neighborhoods 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 there exists a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq U_{1}\cap U_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The colimit 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}_{x}:=\text{colim}_{\mathbf{U}(x)}\mathcal{F}
\]

\end_inset

is called the 
\series bold
stalk 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 More concretely, one has 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}_{x}=\left\{ (U,s)\mid U\text{ is an open neighborhood of }x\text{ and }s\in\mathcal{F}(U)\right\} /\sim,
\]

\end_inset

where two pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{1},s_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{2},s_{2})$
\end_inset

 are equivalent if there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq U_{1}\cap U_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}|_{V}=s_{2}|_{V}$
\end_inset

.
 We often write 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,s]_{x}$
\end_inset

 (or simply 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{x}$
\end_inset

 as the open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 often doesn't matter) to denote the equivalence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,s)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For each open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 we have a canonical map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}(U)\longrightarrow\mathcal{F}_{x},\qquad s\mapsto s_{x},
\]

\end_inset

which sends 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 to the class of 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,s)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{x}$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
germ of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is a morphism of presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then we have an induced map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{x}:=\text{colim}_{\mathbf{U}(x)}\varphi_{U}:\mathcal{F}_{x}\to\mathcal{G}_{x}
\]

\end_inset

of the stalks at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 It sends the equivalence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,s)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 to the class of 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\varphi_{U}(s))$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}_{x}$
\end_inset

 (this is well-defined since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 commutes with restriction maps).
 We obtain a functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 from the category of presheaves to the category of sets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a presheaf of functions, one should think of the stalk 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 as the set of functions defined in some unspecified open neighborhood of
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with values in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 is any category in which filtered colimits exist (for instance the category
 of groups, of rings, of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules, or 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebras, etc...), then the stalk 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is an object in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 and we obtain a functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\mapsto\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 from the category of presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with values in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 to the category 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let us make this more precise for a sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 of groups.
 The group law of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is defined as follows: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,s)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,t)$
\end_inset

.
 Choose an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $W\subseteq U\cap V$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,s)\sim(W,s|_{W})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,t)\sim(W,t_{W})$
\end_inset

 and the product 
\begin_inset Formula $gh$
\end_inset

 is the equivalence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $(W,(s|_{W})(t|_{W}))$
\end_inset

.
 In the same way addition and multiplication is defined on the stalk for
 a sheaf of rings.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Examples of Stalks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}^{\text{ }}$
\end_inset

 be the sheaf of real analytic functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{1},\dots,p_{n})\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 be a germ in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{R}^{n},p}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)$
\end_inset

 be a representative of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is analytic at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{V}$
\end_inset

 is equal to its Taylor series at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=f(p)+\sum_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)(x_{i}-p_{i})+\cdots+\frac{1}{k!}\sum_{i_{1},\dots,i_{k}}\partial_{x_{i_{1}}}\cdots\partial_{x_{i_{k}}}f(p)(x_{i_{1}}-p_{i_{1}})\cdots(x_{i_{k}}-p{}_{i_{k}})+\cdots
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V$
\end_inset

.
 Two real analytic functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 defined in open neighborhoods 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

, respectively, of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 agree on some open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq U_{1}\cap U_{2}$
\end_inset

 if and only if they have the same Taylor expansion around 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 So we have a well-defined map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{R}^{n},p}\to$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Stalk of the sheaf of continuous functions) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X}$
\end_inset

 be the sheaf of continuous 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-valued functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{C}_{X,x}=\left\{ (U,f)\mid U\text{ is and open neighborhood of }x\text{ and }f:U\to\mathbb{R}\text{ is continuous}\right\} /\sim,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)\sim(V,g)$
\end_inset

 if there exists an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap V$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in W$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{W}=g|_{W}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If the germ 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 of a continuous function at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $s(x):=f(x)\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is independent of the choice of representative 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)$
\end_inset

.
 We obtain an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{ev}_{x}:\mathcal{C}_{X,x}\to\mathbb{R},\qquad s\mapsto s(x),
\]

\end_inset

which is surjective because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 contains in particular the germs of all constant functions.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}:=\text{Ker}(\text{ev}_{x})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}/\mathfrak{m}_{x}\cong\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{C}_{X,x}\backslash\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 be represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 By shrinking 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(y)\neq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in U$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous (take 
\begin_inset Formula $(X\backslash f^{-1}\{0\})\cap U$
\end_inset

).
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $1/f$
\end_inset

 exists and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore the complement of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 consists of units of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is a local ring with maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Stalk of the sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 functions) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X}$
\end_inset

 be the sheaf of continuous 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-valued functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{C}_{X,x}=\left\{ (U,f)\mid U\text{ is and open neighborhood of }x\text{ and }f:U\to\mathbb{R}\text{ is continuous}\right\} /\sim,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)\sim(V,g)$
\end_inset

 if there exists an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap V$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in W$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{W}=g|_{W}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If the germ 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 of a continuous function at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $s(x):=f(x)\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is independent of the choice of representative 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)$
\end_inset

.
 We obtain an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{x}:\mathcal{C}_{X,x}\to\mathbb{R},\qquad s\mapsto s(x),
\]

\end_inset

which is surjective because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 contains in particular the germs of all constant functions.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}:=\text{Ker}(e_{x})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}/\mathfrak{m}_{x}\cong\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 We claim that this is the unique maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is a local ring with maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To prove this, we need to show that the complement of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 consists of units of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{C}_{X,x}\backslash\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 be represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 By shrinking 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(y)\neq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in U$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous (take 
\begin_inset Formula $(X\backslash f^{-1}\{0\})\cap U$
\end_inset

).
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $1/f$
\end_inset

 exists and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 be finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an open subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

 denote the sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X;W}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is a local ring.
 Inded, let 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{O}_{x}$
\end_inset

 be a germ and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)$
\end_inset

 be a representative of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 By the very same argument as in the example above, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 does not vanish on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $1/f$
\end_inset

 exists on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 It remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $1/f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 This follows from the stability of the 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 property under composition and the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto1/x$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 map from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{\times}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Working With Stalks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following result will be used very often.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop3.18}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi,\psi:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be two morphisms of presheaves.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf.
 Then the induced map on stalks 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}:\mathcal{F}_{x}\to\mathcal{G}_{x}$
\end_inset

 are injective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}:\mathcal{F}(U)\to\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 is injective for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 are both sheaves, the maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 are bijective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}$
\end_inset

 is bijective for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 are both sheaves, the morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 are equal if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}=\psi_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We give two proofs:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}:\mathcal{F}(U)\to\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 is injective for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}\left([U,s]_{x}\right)=\varphi_{x}\left([U',s']_{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,s]_{x},[U',s']_{x}\in\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U''$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U''\subseteq U\cap U'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}(s)|_{U''}=\varphi_{U'}(s')|_{U''}$
\end_inset

, or in other words 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U''}(s|_{U''})=\varphi_{U''}(s'|_{U''})$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U''}$
\end_inset

 injective, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{U''}=s'|_{U''}$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,s]_{x}=[U',s']_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 was arbitrary, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}:\mathcal{F}_{x}\to\mathcal{G}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is injective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}:\mathcal{F}_{x}\to\mathcal{G}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is injective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}(s)=\varphi_{U}(s')$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $s,s'\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,\varphi_{U}(s)]_{x}=[U,\varphi_{U}(s')]_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}\left([U,s]_{x}\right)=\varphi_{x}\left([U,s']_{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 is injective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,s]_{x}=[U,s']_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{x}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{x}\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{U^{x}}=s'|_{U^{x}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $s=s'$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}$
\end_inset

 is injective, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 was arbitrary, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}:\mathcal{F}(U)\to\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 is injective for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}:\mathcal{F}(U)\to\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 is bijective for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 .
 By 1, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}:\mathcal{F}_{x}\to\mathcal{G}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is injective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, thus it remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 is surjective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,t]_{x}\in\mathcal{G}_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}$
\end_inset

 is surjective, choose 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}(s)=t$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}[U,s]=[U,t]_{x}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 was arbitrary, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 is surjective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 is surjective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 By 1, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}:\mathcal{F}(U)\to\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 is injective, thus it remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 By surjectivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

, we can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $[s^{x},U^{x}]_{x}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}\left([s^{x},U^{x}]_{x}\right)=[t,U]_{x}$
\end_inset

, where we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{x}\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U^{x}}(s^{x})=t|_{U^{x}}$
\end_inset

, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Now observe that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{U^{xy}}(s^{x}|_{U^{xy}}) & =\varphi_{U^{x}}(s^{x})|_{U^{xy}}\\
 & =t|_{U^{xy}}\\
 & =\varphi_{U^{x}}(s^{y})|_{U^{xy}}\\
 & =\varphi_{U^{xy}}(s^{y}|_{U^{xy}}),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U^{xy}}$
\end_inset

 is injective, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{x}|_{U^{xy}}=s^{y}|_{U^{xy}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U^{x}\}_{x\in U}$
\end_inset

 forms an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is sheaf, this implies that there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{U^{x}}=s^{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}(s)=t$
\end_inset

 since
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{U}(s)|_{U^{x}}=\varphi_{U^{x}}(s|_{U^{x}})=t|_{U^{x}}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

 and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\psi$
\end_inset

.
 Then it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}=\psi_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}=\psi_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\neq\psi$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and an 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}(s)\neq\psi_{U}(s)$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[U,\varphi_{U}(s)]_{x} & =\varphi_{x}\left([U,s]_{x}\right)\\
 & =\psi_{x}\left([U,s]_{x}\right)\\
 & =[U,\psi_{U}(s)]_{x}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 This means that there exists there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{x}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{x}\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}(s)|_{U^{x}}=\psi_{U}(s)|_{U^{x}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U^{x}\}_{x\in U}$
\end_inset

 is an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}(s)=\psi_{U}(s)$
\end_inset

.
 Contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
