\begin_layout Standard
we see that 3 and the necessity of the condition in 1 are implied by the
 above claim.
 Moreover, a filtered colimit of injective maps is always injective again.
 Indeed, this follows either from abstract nonsense or we can argue directly:
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{0},t_{0}\in\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}(s_{0})=\varphi_{x}(t_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{0}$
\end_inset

 be represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(s,U)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,V)$
\end_inset

.
 By shrinking 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, we may assume 
\begin_inset Formula $U=V$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{U}(s)_{x} & =\varphi_{x}(s_{0})\\
 & =\varphi_{x}(t_{0})\\
 & =\varphi_{U}(t)_{x},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $W\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{W}(s|_{W}) & =\varphi_{U}(s)|_{W}\\
 & =\varphi_{U}(t)|_{W}\\
 & =\varphi_{W}(t|_{W}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

As 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{W}$
\end_inset

 is injective, we find 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{W}=t|_{W}$
\end_inset

 and hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
s_{0} & =s_{x}\\
 & =t_{x}\\
 & =t_{0}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore the condition in 1 is also sufficient.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Hence we are done if we show that the bijectivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

 implies the surjectivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

 we choose an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{x}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{x}\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 and we choose an element 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{x}\in\mathcal{F}(U^{x})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U^{x}}(s^{x})=t|_{U^{x}}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that we can do this because 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U^{x}\}_{x\in U}$
\end_inset

 is an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and for 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in U$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{U^{xy}}(s^{x}|_{U^{xy}}) & =\varphi_{U^{x}}(s^{x})|_{U^{xy}}\\
 & =t|_{U^{xy}}\\
 & =\varphi_{U^{y}}(s^{y})|_{U^{xy}}\\
 & =\varphi_{U^{xy}}(s^{y}|_{U^{xy}}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

As we already know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U^{xy}}$
\end_inset

 is injective, this shows 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{x}|_{U^{xy}}=s^{y}|_{U^{xy}}$
\end_inset

 and the sheaf condition ensures that we find 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{U^{x}}=s^{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}(s)_{x}=t_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}(s)=t$
\end_inset

.
 
