\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We call a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 of sheaves 
\series bold
injective 
\series default
(respectively 
\series bold
surjective
\series default
, respectively 
\series bold
bijective
\series default
) if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}:\mathcal{F}_{x}\to\mathcal{G}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is injective (respectively surjective, respectively bijective) for all
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of sheaves.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is injective (respectively bijective) if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}:\mathcal{F}(U)\to\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 is injective (respectively bijective) for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is surjective if and only if for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 and every 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 there exist an open covering 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 (depending on 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

) and sections 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}\in\mathcal{F}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U_{i}}(s_{i})=t|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, if locally we can find a preimage of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 But the surjectivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 does not imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}:\mathcal{F}(U)\to\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 is surjective for all open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, in the proof above we needed injectivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U^{xy}}$
\end_inset

 in order to patch up the various local sections.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Similary, as we defined the notions of injectivity or surjectivity 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stalkwise
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, we also define the notion of an exact sequence of sheaves of groups 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stalkwise
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A sequence 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
