\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be sheaves on a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 A morphism of sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is injective (respectively surjective, respectively bijective) if and only
 if its restriction 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi|_{U_{i}}:\mathcal{F}|_{U_{i}}\to\mathcal{G}|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 to morphisms of sheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 is injective (respectively surjective, respectively bijective) for all
 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 because these notions are defined via the stalks.
 But note that the existence of the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is crucial.
 There exists sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 are not isomorphic.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sheafification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a functorial way to attach to a presheaf a sheaf:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propsheafification}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(\widetilde{\mathcal{F}},\iota_{\mathcal{F}})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{\widetilde{F}}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F}}:\mathcal{F}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 is a morphism of presheaves, such that the following holds: If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is a morphism of presheaves, then there exists a unique morphism of sheaves
 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}:\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}\circ\iota_{\mathcal{F}}=\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(\widetilde{\mathcal{F}},\iota_{\mathcal{F}})$
\end_inset

 is unique up to unique isomorphism.
 Moreover, the following properties hold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For all 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in X$
\end_inset

, the map of stalks 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F},x_{0}}:\mathcal{F}_{x_{0}}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is bijective.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and every morphism of presheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 there exists a unique morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}:\mathcal{\widetilde{F}\to\widetilde{G}}$
\end_inset

 making the diagram 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
mathcal{F} 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
iota _{
\backslash
mathcal{F}} "] 
\backslash
arrow[d, "
\backslash
varphi ", swap] & 
\backslash
widetilde{
\backslash
mathcal{F}} 
\backslash
arrow[d, "
\backslash
widetilde{
\backslash
varphi }"]  
\backslash

\backslash
  
\backslash
mathcal{G} 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
iota _{
\backslash
mathcal{G}} "]  & 
\backslash
widetilde{
\backslash
mathcal{F}} 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 commutative.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\mapsto\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 is a functor from the category of presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to the category of sheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 is called the sheaf associated to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 or the 
\series bold
sheafification 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 open, elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U)$
\end_inset

 are by definition families of elements in the stalks of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, which locally give rise to sections of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 More precisely, we define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U):=\left\{ (s_{x}^{x})_{x\in U}\in\prod_{x\in U}\mathcal{F}_{x}\mid\forall x_{0}\in U,\text{ }\exists\text{ open neighborhood }U_{0}\subseteq U\text{ of }x_{0}\text{ and }s\in\mathcal{F}(U_{0})\text{ such that }s_{x}^{x}=s_{x},\forall x\in U_{0}.\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Here we use the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{x}^{x}$
\end_inset

 for a germ at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with representative 
\begin_inset Formula $(U^{x},s^{x})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{x}$
\end_inset

 is a sufficiently small neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{x}\in\mathcal{F}(U^{x})$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 the restriction map 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(V)\to\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U)$
\end_inset

 is induced by the natural projection 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{x\in V}\mathcal{F}_{x}\to\prod_{x\in U}\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{x}^{x})_{x\in V}|_{U}=(s_{x}^{x})_{x\in U}$
\end_inset

).
 To see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be a covering of an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{x}^{x})_{x\in U_{i}}\in\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{x}^{x})_{x\in U_{i}}|_{U_{ij}}=(s_{x}^{x})_{x\in U_{ij}}=(s_{x}^{x})_{x\in U_{j}}|_{U_{ij}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then it is easy to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{x}^{x})_{x\in U}$
\end_inset

 is the unique section such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{x}^{x})_{x\in U}|_{U_{i}}=(s_{x}^{x})_{x\in U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Now we prove the two properties stated in the proposition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 open, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F},U}:\mathcal{F}(U)\to\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $s\mapsto(s_{x})_{x\in U}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F},x_{0}}:\mathcal{F}_{x_{0}}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is bijective.
 First we will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F},x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is injective: let 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 be two germs at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(s,U)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,U)$
\end_inset

 respectively, and suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F},x_{0}}(s_{x_{0}})=\iota_{\mathcal{F},x_{0}}(t_{x_{0}})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{x})_{x\in U}=(t_{x})_{x\in U}$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{x_{0}}=t_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F},x}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Now let us show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F},x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{0}$
\end_inset

 be a germ in 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,(s_{x}^{x})_{x\in U})$
\end_inset

 is a representative of 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Then in some open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}(U_{0})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{x}^{x}=s_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this means 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{0},(s_{x})_{x\in U_{0}})$
\end_inset

 is a representative of 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F},x}(s_{x})=s_{0}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{x}\in\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is the germ at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with representative 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{0},s)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be a morphism.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}:\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

 by defining, for each open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}_{U}:\mathcal{\widetilde{F}}(U)\to\widetilde{\mathcal{G}}(U)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}\left((s_{x}^{x})_{x\in U}\right)=(\varphi_{x}(s_{x}^{x}))_{x\in U}$
\end_inset

 (in terms of representatives at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

, we are mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $(U^{x_{0}},s^{x_{0}})$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $(U^{x_{0}},\varphi_{U^{x_{0}}}(s^{x_{0}}))$
\end_inset

).
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 is the unique morphism making the diagram commutative.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}:\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

 is another morphism making the diagram commute, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\circ\iota_{\mathcal{F}}=\iota_{\mathcal{G}}\circ\varphi=\widetilde{\varphi}\circ\iota_{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}_{x}\circ\iota_{\mathcal{F},x}=\widetilde{\varphi}_{x}\circ\iota_{\mathcal{F},x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F},x}$
\end_inset

 is a bijection, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}_{x}=\widetilde{\psi}_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}=\widetilde{\psi}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop3.18})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If we assume in addition that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf, then the morphism of sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{G}}:\mathcal{G}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

, which is bijective on stalks, is an isomorphism by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop3.18})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Composing the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{G}}^{-1}$
\end_inset

, we obtain the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{G}}^{-1}\circ\widetilde{\varphi}:\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, the uniqueness of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\widetilde{\mathcal{F}},\iota_{\mathcal{F}})$
\end_inset

 is a formal consequence.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmahomshpsh}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then there is a bijection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\text{\emph{Hom}}_{\mathbf{Sh}(X)}(\widetilde{\mathcal{F}},\mathcal{G}) & \longleftrightarrow & \text{\emph{Hom}}_{\mathbf{Psh}(Y)}(\mathcal{F},\mathcal{G}),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

which is functorial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

, then there exists a unique morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}:\widetilde{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}\circ\iota_{\mathcal{F}}=\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}:\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

, then we 
\emph on
define 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:=\widetilde{\varphi}\circ\iota_{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

.
 Functoriality in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is an easy exercise.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sheafification of Presheaf of Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be a set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf of functions with values in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U)\cong\left\{ g:U\to E\mid\exists\text{ open covering }\{V_{i}\}\text{ of }U\text{ such that }g|_{V_{i}}\in\mathcal{F}(V_{i})\text{ for all }i\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{x}^{x})_{x\in U}\in\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, choose an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{x}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 together with 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{x}\in\mathcal{F}(V^{x})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{x}\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{y}^{x}=f_{y}^{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in V^{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Now define a function 
\begin_inset Formula $g:U\to E$
\end_inset

 as follows: for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x):=g^{x}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 We have to be sure that this is well-defined (i.e.
 does not depend on the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{x}$
\end_inset

), so suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V^{y}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
g(x) & =g^{y}(x)\\
 & =g_{x}^{y}(x)\\
 & =g_{x}^{x}(x)\\
 & =g^{x}(x),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which shows that this function is well-defined.
 The point here is that 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{y}$
\end_inset

 agree on some neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $(V^{x},g^{x})$
\end_inset

 can be used as a representative for all germs 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{z}^{z}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in V^{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $(V^{y},g^{y})$
\end_inset

 can be used as a representative for all germs 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{z}^{z}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in V^{y}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, both 
\begin_inset Formula $(V^{x},g^{x})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V^{y},g^{y})$
\end_inset

 are representatives for the germ 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}^{x}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V^{x}\cap V^{y}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this means that there is a sufficiently small neighborhood
 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{x}|_{V}=g^{x}|_{V}=g^{y}|_{V}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

It is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $g|_{V^{x}}=g^{x}\in\mathcal{F}(V^{x})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we have constructed a well-defined map given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{x}^{x})_{x\in U}\mapsto g$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, if we start with a 
\begin_inset Formula $g:U\to E$
\end_inset

 such that there exists an open covering 
\begin_inset Formula $\{V_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g|_{V_{i}}\in\mathcal{F}(V_{i})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, then it's easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $(g_{x})_{x\in U}\in\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be a set and denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{X}$
\end_inset

 the sheaf of locally constant functions, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{X}(U):=\{f:U\to E\mid f\text{ is locally constant}\}.
\]

\end_inset

This is the sheafification of the presheaf of constant functions with values
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 The sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{X}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
constant sheaf with value 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sheaves and Etale Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Bundles 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{samepage}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{slice category}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}/c$
\end_inset

 of a category 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 over an object 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 is the category whose objects are morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $f:d\to c$
\end_inset

 and whose morphisms from 
\begin_inset Formula $f:d\to c$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $f':d'\to c$
\end_inset

 are the morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $g:d\to d'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f'\circ g=f$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

