\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:(E,\pi)\to(E',\pi')$
\end_inset

 be a morphism in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Top}/X$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{U}:\mathcal{F}_{\pi}(U)\to\mathcal{F}_{\pi'}(U)$
\end_inset

 to be the function that maps a section 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}_{\pi}(U)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ s$
\end_inset

.
 The maps 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{U}$
\end_inset

 are the components of a natural transformation from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{\pi}\to\mathcal{F}_{\pi'}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we have constructed a functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma:\mbox{\mathbf{Top}}/X\to\mathbf{Sh}(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
From 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Psh}(X)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Etale}(X)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{\mathcal{F}}:=\coprod_{x\in X}\mathcal{F}_{x}=\bigcup_{x\in X}\left\{ (x,s_{0})\mid s_{0}\in\mathcal{F}_{x}\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathcal{F}}:E_{\mathcal{F}}\to X$
\end_inset

 be the obvious projection map (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,s)\mapsto x$
\end_inset

).
 For each open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and section 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,s]=\{(x,s_{x})\mid x\in U\}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 be the topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 with the collection of all 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,s]$
\end_inset

 as a subbasis.
 We claim that the collection of all 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,s]$
\end_inset

 is actually a basis for this topology.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,s],[V,t]\in\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{0},s_{x_{0}})\in[U,s]\cap[V,t]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in U\cap V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{x_{0}}=t_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that there exists a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}\subseteq U\cap V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{U_{0}}=t|_{U_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{x}=t_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $[U_{0},s|_{U_{0}}]\subseteq[U,s]\cap[V,t]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Finally, we want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathcal{F}}:E_{\mathcal{F}}\to X$
\end_inset

 a local homeomorphism with respect to this topology.
 To see why, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 maps basis elements to basis elements (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,s]\mapsto U$
\end_inset

).
 Thus, it must be an open mapping.
 Also, if 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,s_{0})\in E_{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

, then after choosing a representative of 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{0}$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,s)$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,s_{0})\in[U,s]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi|_{[U,s]}:[U,s]\to U$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi|_{[U,s]}$
\end_inset

 is an open mapping and a bijection, hence its inverse must be continuous.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
co-unit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p:B\to X$
\end_inset

 be any local homeomorphism, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{p}$
\end_inset

 its sheaf of sections, and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{F_{p}}:B_{F_{p}}\to X$
\end_inset

 the associated sheaf of germs.
 Define a map 
\begin_inset Formula $k:B\to B_{F_{p}}$
\end_inset

 as follow: If 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in B$
\end_inset

, there exist a local section 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 through 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, defined on an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in s(V)$
\end_inset

 (we proved this earlier).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $k(b)=(f(b),[s]_{f(b)})$
\end_inset

 be the germ of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $f(b)$
\end_inset

.
 The definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $k(b)$
\end_inset

 does not depend on which section through 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is chosen (we proved this earlier too).
 This gives us the following commutative diagram:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[column sep=small] B 
\backslash
arrow[dr,"p" swap] 
\backslash
arrow[rr,"k"] && B_{F_{p}} 
\backslash
arrow[dl," p_{F_{p}} "] 
\backslash

\backslash
 & X 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Etale}(X)$
\end_inset

-arrow from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{F_{p}}$
\end_inset

, in fact, it is an iso.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
unit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{U}:F(U)\to F_{p_{F}}(U)$
\end_inset

 by putting, for 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in F(U)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{U}(s)=s_{U}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{U}:U\to A_{F}$
\end_inset

 is defined by putting 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{U}(x)=(x,[s]_{x})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Direct and Inverse Images of Sheaves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 denotes a continuous map of topological spaces.
 We will now see how to use 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in order to attach a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 (direct image) and to a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 (inverse image).
 We start with the direct image.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Direct Image
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a continuous map.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We define a presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{*}\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(f_{*}\mathcal{F})(V)=\mathcal{F}(f^{-1}(V))
\]

\end_inset

for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 The restriction maps are given by the restriction maps for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{*}\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
direct image of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 Whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\mathcal{F}_{1}\to\mathcal{F}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a morphism of presheaves, the family of maps 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{*}(\varphi)_{V}:=\varphi_{f^{-1}(V)}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 open is a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{*}(\varphi):f_{*}\mathcal{F}_{1}\to f_{*}\mathcal{F}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore we obtain a functor 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{*}$
\end_inset

 from the category of presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to the category of presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a continuous map, 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be a set, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{X}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{Y}$
\end_inset

 be the sheaf of locally constant 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

-valued functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 open and for locally constant map 
\begin_inset Formula $g:V\to E$
\end_inset

 the composition 
\begin_inset Formula $g\circ p:p^{-1}(V)\to E$
\end_inset

 is locally constant.
 Hence we obtain a morphism of sheaves
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi:E_{Y}\to p_{*}E_{X}.
\]

\end_inset

Now suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is surjective, that 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 has the quotient topology of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 has connected fibers.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 open, a locally constant map 
\begin_inset Formula $h:p^{-1}(V)\to E$
\end_inset

 is the same as a continuous map if we endow 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 with the discrete topology.
 The restriction of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 to the fibers of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is constant and hence by the universal property of the quotient topology
 there exists a unique continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $g:V\to E$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\circ p=h$
\end_inset

.
 Hence we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism in this case.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{*}\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{V_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an open covering of an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}\in f_{*}\mathcal{F}(V_{i})=\mathcal{F}(f^{-1}(V_{i}))$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}|{}_{f^{-1}(V_{ij})}=s_{j}|{}_{f^{-1}(V_{ij})}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f^{-1}(V_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 is an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

, and so by the sheaf property of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}(f^{-1}(V))=f_{*}\mathcal{F}(V)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{f^{-1}(V_{i})}=s_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{*}$
\end_inset

 defines a functor 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{*}:\mathbf{Sh}(X)\to\mathbf{Sh}(Y)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propdirectstalk}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{*}\mathcal{F})_{f(x)}\cong\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathcal{F},x}:(f_{*}\mathcal{F})_{f(x)}\to\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 be the map given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathcal{F},x}\left([V,s]_{f(x)}\right)=[f^{-1}(V),s]_{x}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is an open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}(f^{-1}(V))$
\end_inset

.
 We need to show that this map is well-defined.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(V',s')$
\end_inset

 be another representative of the equivalence class 
\begin_inset Formula $[V,s]_{f(x)}$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V''$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $V''\subseteq V\cap V'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{f^{-1}(V'')}=s'|_{f^{-1}(V'')}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(V'')$
\end_inset

 is an open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(V'')\subseteq f^{-1}(V)\cap f^{-1}(V')$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi_{\mathcal{F},x}\left([V',s']_{f(x)}\right) & =[f^{-1}(V'),s']_{x}\\
 & =[f^{-1}(V),s]_{x}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus this map is well-defined.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathcal{F},x}$
\end_inset

 is bijective, we simply describe the inverse map: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathcal{F},x}^{-1}:\mathcal{F}_{x}\to(f_{*}\mathcal{F})_{f(x)}$
\end_inset

 be the map given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathcal{F},x}^{-1}\left([U,s]_{x}\right)=[f(U),s]_{f(x)}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that we need 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 to be an injective open map for this it to be well-defined (It is not enough
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is an open mapping.
 We also need 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}(f^{-1}(f(U)))$
\end_inset

, so we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(f(U))=U$
\end_inset

.
 However in general we only have 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(f(U))\supseteq U$
\end_inset

).
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathcal{F},x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathcal{F},x}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are inverse to each other.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Inverse Image
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a continuous map and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Define a presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{+}\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{+}\mathcal{G}(U)=\lim_{\substack{V\supseteq f(U)\\
V\subseteq Y\text{ open}
}
}\mathcal{G}(V).
\]

\end_inset

the restriction maps being induced by the restriction maps on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be the sheafification of 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{+}\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
inverse image of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

More concretely, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{+}\mathcal{G}(U)=\left\{ (V,t)\mid V\text{ is open subset of }Y\text{ such that }f(U)\subseteq V,\text{ and }t\in\mathcal{G}(V)\right\} /\sim,
\]

\end_inset

where two pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V',t')$
\end_inset

 are equivalent if there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V''$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f(U)\subseteq V''\subseteq V\cap V'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $t|_{V''}=t'|_{V''}$
\end_inset

.
 We shall write 
\begin_inset Formula $[V,t]_{f(U)}$
\end_inset

 (or simply 
\begin_inset Formula $[V,t]$
\end_inset

 to ease notation) for the equivalence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,t)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U'$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U'\subseteq U$
\end_inset

, then the restriction map is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $[V,t]|_{U'}=[V,t]_{f(U')}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let's see why 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{+}\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 can fail to be a sheaf.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $[V_{i},t_{i}]\in f^{+}\mathcal{G}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $[V_{i},t_{i}]|_{U_{ij}}=[V_{j},t_{j}]|_{U_{ij}}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this means there exists an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $V'_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(U_{ij})\subseteq V'_{i,j}\subseteq V_{ij}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}|_{V'_{i,j}}=t_{j}|_{V'_{i,j}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If there existed 
\begin_inset Formula $[V,t]\in f^{+}\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $[V,t]|_{U_{i}}=[V_{i},t_{i}]_{f(U_{i})}$
\end_inset

, then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 there would exist an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $V'_{i}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(U_{i})\subseteq V'_{i}\subseteq V_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t|_{V'_{i}}=t_{i}|_{V'_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 By replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $[V_{i},t_{i}]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $[V'_{i},t_{i}|_{V'_{i}}]$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $V'_{i,j}\subseteq V'_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the inclusion of a subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, we also write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}|_{X}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 and we write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}(X):=(f^{-1}(\mathcal{G}))(X)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The construction of 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{+}\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 and hence of 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is functorial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore we obtain a functor 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}:\mathbf{PSh}(Y)\to\mathbf{Sh}(X)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is an open continuous map, then for 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 open one has 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{+}\mathcal{G}(U)\cong\mathcal{G}(f(U))$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $[V,t]\in f^{+}\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $[V,t]=[f(U),t|_{f(U)}]$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the map sending the element 
\begin_inset Formula $[V,t]\in f^{+}\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 to the element 
\begin_inset Formula $t|_{f(U)}\in\mathcal{G}(f(U))$
\end_inset

 is well-defined and gives rise to an isomorphism of presheaves.
 Moreover, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{+}\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{+}\mathcal{G}=f^{-1}\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the inclusion of an open subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $U=X$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, then for every sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U'\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 open, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{G}|_{U}(U')=\mathcal{G}(U').
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propinversestalk}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(f^{-1}\mathcal{G})_{x}\cong\mathcal{G}_{f(x)}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{+}\mathcal{G}_{x}\cong\mathcal{G}_{f(x)}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propsheafification})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(f^{+}\mathcal{G})_{x}=\left\{ (U,[V,t])\mid U\text{ is an open neighborhood of }x\text{ and }[V,t]\in f^{+}\mathcal{G}(U)\right\} /\sim,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $[V,t]$
\end_inset

 denotes the equivalence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,t)\in f^{+}\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,[V,t])\sim(U',[V',t'])$
\end_inset

 if there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U''$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U''\subseteq U\cap U'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[V,t]|_{U''}=[V',t']|_{U''}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 and there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V''$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(U'')$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $V''\subseteq V\cap V'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t|_{V''}=t'|_{V''}$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,[V,t]]_{x}$
\end_inset

 denotes the equivalence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,[V,t])\in f^{+}\mathcal{G}_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\mathcal{G},x}:f^{+}\mathcal{G}_{x}\to\mathcal{G}_{f(x)}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\mathcal{G},x}\left([U,[V,t]]_{x}\right)=[V,t]_{f(x)}$
\end_inset

.
 We need to show that this map is well-defined.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(U',[V',t'])$
\end_inset

 be another representative of the equivalence class 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,[V,t]]_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Then as described above, there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U''$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U''\subseteq U\cap U'$
\end_inset

 and there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V''$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(U'')$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(U'')\subseteq V''\subseteq V\cap V'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t|_{V''}=t'|_{V''}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $V''$
\end_inset

 is also an open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

, this implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lambda_{\mathcal{G},x}\left([U',[V',t']]_{x}\right) & =[V',t']_{f(x)}\\
 & =[V,t]_{f(x)}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus this map is well-defined.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\mathcal{G},x}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Suppose
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lambda_{\mathcal{G},x}\left([U,[V,t]]_{x}\right) & =[V,t]_{f(x)}\\
 & =[V',t']_{f(x)}\\
 & =\lambda_{\mathcal{G},x}\left([U',[V',t']]_{x}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Then there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V''$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $V''\subseteq V\cap V'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t|_{V''}=t'|_{V''}$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $U''=f^{-1}(V'')\cap U\cap U'$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $U''$
\end_inset

 is an open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U''\subseteq U\cap U'$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V''$
\end_inset

 is an open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(U'')$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $V''\subseteq V\cap V'$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $t|_{V''}=t|_{V''}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,[V,t]]_{x}=[U',[V',t']]_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Finally, we that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\mathcal{G},x}$
\end_inset

 is is onto (which will imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\mathcal{G},x}$
\end_inset

 is a bijection since we've already shown it is injective).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $[V,t]_{f(x)}\in\mathcal{G}_{f(x)}$
\end_inset

.
 We just need to find an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(U)\subseteq V$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\mathcal{G},x}\left([U,[V,t]]_{x}\right)=[V,t]_{f(x)}$
\end_inset

.
 In fact 
\begin_inset Formula $U=f^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 does the trick, and we are done.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Adjunction between direct image and inverse image
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Direct image and inverse image are functors that are adjoint to each other.
 More precisely:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propadjunctiondirectinverse}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Then there is a bijection 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\text{\emph{Hom}}_{\mathbf{Psh}(X)}(f^{+}\mathcal{G},\mathcal{F}) & \longleftrightarrow & \text{\emph{Hom}}_{\mathbf{Psh}(Y)}(\mathcal{G},f_{*}\mathcal{F})\\
\varphi & \mapsto & \varphi^{\flat}\\
\psi^{\#} & \mapsfrom & \psi,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

which is functorial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf, then there is a bijection
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\text{\emph{Hom}}_{\mathbf{Sh}(X)}(f^{-1}\mathcal{G},\mathcal{F}) & \longleftrightarrow & \text{\emph{Hom}}_{\mathbf{Psh}(Y)}(\mathcal{G},f_{*}\mathcal{F}),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

which is functorial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is also a sheaf then there is a bijection
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\text{\emph{Hom}}_{\mathbf{Sh}(X)}(f^{-1}\mathcal{G},\mathcal{F}) & \longleftrightarrow & \text{\emph{Hom}}_{\mathbf{Sh}(Y)}(\mathcal{G},f_{*}\mathcal{F}),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

which is functorial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:f^{+}\mathcal{G}\to\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{\flat}:\mathcal{G}\to f_{*}\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 as follows: let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be open in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathcal{G}(V)$
\end_inset

.
 Then we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{V}^{\flat}(t)=\varphi_{f^{-1}(V)}\left([V,t]_{f\left(f^{-1}(V)\right)}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi:\mathcal{G}\to f_{*}\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi^{\#}:f^{+}\mathcal{G}\to\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 as follows: let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $[V,t]_{f(U)}\in f^{+}\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Then we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{U}^{\#}\left([V,t]_{f(U)}\right)=\psi_{V}(t)|_{U}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let us check that these two maps are inverse to each other, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi^{\flat})^{\#}=\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi^{\#})^{\flat}=\psi$
\end_inset

.
 First we show 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi^{\flat})^{\#}=\varphi$
\end_inset

: let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $[V,t]_{f(U)}\in f^{+}\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\varphi^{\flat})_{U}^{\#}\left([V,t]_{f(U)}\right) & =\varphi_{V}^{\flat}(t)|_{U}\\
 & =\varphi_{f^{-1}(V)}\left([V,t]_{f\left(f^{-1}(V)\right)}\right)|_{U}\\
 & =\varphi_{U}\left([V,t]_{f\left(f^{-1}(V)\right)}|_{U}\right)\\
 & =\varphi_{U}\left([V,t]_{f(U)}\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we used the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq f^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(U)\subseteq V$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we show 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi^{\#})^{\flat}=\psi$
\end_inset

: let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be open in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathcal{G}(V)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\psi^{\#})_{V}^{\flat}\left(t\right) & =\psi_{f^{-1}(V)}^{\#}\left([V,t]_{f\left(f^{-1}(V)\right)}\right)\\
 & =\psi_{V}(t)|_{f^{-1}(V)}\\
 & =\psi_{V}(t).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Therefore these two maps are inverse to each other.
 Moreover, it is straightforward - albeit quite cumbersome - to check that
 the constructed maps are functorial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 The last part of the proposition follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmahomshpsh})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We will almost never use the concrete description of 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 in the sequel.
 Very often we are given 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

, and a morphism of shaves 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}:\mathcal{G}\to f_{*}\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Then usually it is sufficient to understand for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 the map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{x}^{\#}:\mathcal{G}_{f(x)}\to(f^{-1}\mathcal{G})_{x}\cong\mathcal{F}_{x},
\]

\end_inset

induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\#}:f^{-1}\mathcal{G}\to\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 on stalks.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Ringed Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout the rest of this article, let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\widehat{\mathbb{N}}_{0}=\mathbb{N}\cup\{0,\infty,\omega\}$
\end_inset

.
 Ringed spaces formalize the idea of giving a geometric object by specifying
 its underlying topological space and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

functions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on all open subsets of this space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
An 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
ringed space 
\series default
is a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a topological space and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of commutative 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebras on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The sheaf of rings 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
structure sheaf 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\series bold
locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space 
\series default
is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 such that the stalk 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is a local ring for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 We then denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 the maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 and by 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa(x):=\mathcal{O}_{X,x}/\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 its residue field.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Usually we will denote a (locally) 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 simply by 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Our principle example will be sheaves of real-valued 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of a finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 the sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 functions: For all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha}(U)=\{f:U\to\mathbb{R}\mid f\text{ is }C^{\alpha}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras.
 The same argument as for sheaves of continuous functions yields the following
 observation: For all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 the stalk 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{X,x}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is a local ring.
 In particular 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 is a locally 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-ringed space.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Another example comes from Algebraic Geometry:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 be an algebraically closed field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible affine algebraic set.
 The space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is equipped with the Zariski topology.
 Recall that a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:U\to k$
\end_inset

 from an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to the field 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
regular 
\series default
at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in X$
\end_inset

 if there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 and there are polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x)=\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 With this in mind, we define the structure sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 as follows: for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)=\{\varphi:U\to k\mid\varphi\text{ is regular}\}.
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Morphisms of (Locally) Ringed Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=(Y,\mathcal{O}_{Y})$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces.
 A 
\series bold
morphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to Y$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\flat})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is a continuous map of the underlying topological spaces and where 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}:\mathcal{O}_{Y}\to f_{*}\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is a homomorphism of sheaves of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebras on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The datum of 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to the datum of a homomorphism of sheaves of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebras 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\#}:f^{-1}\mathcal{O}_{Y}\to\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propadjunctiondirectinverse})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Usually we simply write 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\#})$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\flat})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Morphisms of 
\emph on
locally 
\emph default
ringed spaces have to satisfy an additional property.
 To state this property, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces and for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 let 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}$
\end_inset

 be the composition of induced homomorphisms on the stalks 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
mathcal{O}_{Y 
\backslash
text{,} f(x)} 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
lambda _{
\backslash
mathcal{O}_Y 
\backslash
text{,} x }   "] & f^{-1} (
\backslash
mathcal{O}_Y )_x  
\backslash
arrow[r, "f^{
\backslash
# } _x "]  & 
\backslash
mathcal{O}_{X 
\backslash
text{,}x} 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}:=f^{\#}{}_{x}\circ\lambda_{\mathcal{O}_{Y},x}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\mathcal{O}_{Y},x}$
\end_inset

 is the isomorphism constructed in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propinversestalk})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 We can better understand 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}$
\end_inset

 by following an element 
\begin_inset Formula $[V,t]_{f(x)}\in\mathcal{O}_{Y,f(x)}$
\end_inset

 under the composition:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[V,t]_{f(x)} & \mapsto[f^{-1}(V),[V,t]_{f(f^{-1}(V))}]_{x}\\
 & \mapsto[f^{-1}(V),f_{f^{-1}(V)}^{\#}([V,t]_{f(f^{-1}(V))})]_{x}\\
 & =[f^{-1}(V),f_{V}^{\flat}(t)]_{x},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the last equality follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propadjunctiondirectinverse})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces.
 We define a 
\series bold
morphism of locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to Y$
\end_inset

 
\series default
to be a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\flat})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, the homomorphisms of local rings 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}:\mathcal{O}_{Y,f(x)}\to\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
local 
\series default
(i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}(\mathfrak{m}_{f(x)})\subseteq\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Y}$
\end_inset

 are sheaves of functions, the condition that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}$
\end_inset

 is local is equivalent to the condition that if 
\begin_inset Formula $[V,t]_{f(x)}\in\mathcal{O}_{Y,f(x)}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $t(x)=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{V}^{\flat}(t)(x)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In general there exist locally ringed spaces and morphisms of ringed spaces
 between them that are not morphisms of 
\emph on
locally 
\emph default
ringed spaces.
 For spaces with functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 functions such as the premanifolds defined below, we will see that every
 morphism of ringed spaces is automatically a morphism of locally ringed
 spaces.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The composition of morphisms of (locally) 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces is defined in the obvious way using the compatibility of
 direct images with composition (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(g\circ f)_{*}=g_{*}\circ f_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 We obtain the category of (locally) 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In general, 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\#}$
\end_inset

) is an additional datum for a morphism.
 For instance it might happen that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the identity but 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 is not an isomorphism of sheaves.
 We will usually encounter the simpler case that the structure sheaf is
 a sheaf of functions on open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 is given by composition with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 The following special case and its globalization is the main example.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subseteq W$
\end_inset

 be open subsets of finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 Every 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 map 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 defines by composition a morphism of locally 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\flat}):(X,\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha})\to(Y,\mathcal{C}_{Y}^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
f_{U}^{\flat}:\mathcal{C}_{Y}^{\alpha}(U) & \longrightarrow & f_{*}(\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha})(U)=\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha}(f^{-1}(U))\\
t & \mapsto & t\circ f
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 open.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The induced map on stalks 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}:\mathcal{C}_{Y,f(x)}^{\alpha}\to\mathcal{C}_{X,x}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is then also given by composing an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-valued 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, defined in some neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, which yields an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-valued 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $t\circ f$
\end_inset

 defined in some neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\flat}):(X,\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha})\to(Y,\mathcal{C}_{Y}^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 be any morphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces.
 We claim: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\flat})$
\end_inset

 is automatically a morphism of 
\emph on
locally 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For all 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 open the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{U}^{\flat}:\mathcal{C}_{Y}^{\alpha}(U)\to\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha}(f^{-1}(U))$
\end_inset

 is automatically given by the map 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mapsto t\circ f$
\end_inset

.
 Note that then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 map (choose a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

; considering for 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 projections to the coordinates shows that each component of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 map).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To show 1 let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:=f_{x}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B:=\mathcal{C}_{X,x}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $A:=\mathcal{C}_{Y,f(x)}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A\to B$
\end_inset

 is a homomorphism of local 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{m}_{A}=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B/\mathfrak{m}_{B}=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is automatically local, equivalently that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{m}_{B})$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 induces an injective homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A/\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{m}_{B})\hookrightarrow B/\mathfrak{m}_{B}=\mathbb{R}.
\]

\end_inset

As a homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras, it is automatically surjective (indeed 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 maps to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

), hence 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{m}_{B})\cong\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a field and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{m}_{B})$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let us show 2.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 be open and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in f^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the commutative diagram of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphisms 
