\begin_layout Standard
The evaluation maps are surjective.
 Hence there exists a homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 making the lower rectangle commutative if and only if one has 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}(\text{Ker}(\text{ev}_{f(x)}))\subseteq\text{Ker}(\text{ev}_{x})$
\end_inset

.
 But this latter condition is satisfied because 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}$
\end_inset

 is local by 1.
 Moreover, as a homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras, one must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota=\text{id}_{\mathbb{R}}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore we find 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{V}^{\flat}(t)(x)=t(f(x))$
\end_inset

, which shows 2.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces is an isomorphism in the category of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}:\mathcal{O}_{Y,f(x)}\to\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebras for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\flat})$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism and 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism of sheaves of rings.
 We claim that if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, note that since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}=\pi_{\mathcal{O}_{X},x}\circ f_{x}^{\flat}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathcal{O}_{X},x}$
\end_inset

 is the isomorphism constructed in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propdirectstalk})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Open embedding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 be open.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\mathcal{O}_{X|U})$
\end_inset

 is a locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space, which we usually denote simply by 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Such a locally ringed 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-space is called an 
\series bold
open subspace 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 There is an 
\series bold
inclusion morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $i:U\to X$
\end_inset

 
\series default
of locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces, where the continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $i:U\to X$
\end_inset

 is the inclusion of the underlying topological spaces and where 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 is given by the restriction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U')\to i_{*}(\mathcal{O}_{X|U})(U')=\mathcal{O}_{X}(U\cap U')$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $U'\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 open.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{\#}:i^{-1}\mathcal{O}_{X}\to\mathcal{O}_{X|U}$
\end_inset

 is the identity.
 In particular 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{x}$
\end_inset

 is the identity for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 of locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces, we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U}:U\to Y$
\end_inset

 the composition 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ i$
\end_inset

 of morphisms of locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Finally, a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $j:(Z,\mathcal{O}_{Z})\to(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 of locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces is called an 
\series bold
open embedding 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $U:=j(Z)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 induces an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $(Z,\mathcal{O}_{Z})\cong(U,\mathcal{O}_{X|U})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 of locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces is called a 
\series bold
local isomorphism 
\series default
if there exists an open covering 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U_{i}}:U_{i}\to Y$
\end_inset

 is an open embedding for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In other words, a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a local isomorphism if there exists an open covering 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 an open subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 induces an isomorpism 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\cong V_{i}$
\end_inset

 of locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces is a local isomorphism if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a local homeomorphism and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}:\mathcal{O}_{Y,f(x)}\to\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gluing Ringed Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(X_{i},\mathcal{F}_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be a collection of ringed spaces, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 be open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{i,j}:X_{i,j}\to X_{j,i}$
\end_inset

 be homeomorphisms for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
  Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X:=\coprod_{i\in I}X_{i}/\sim
\]

\end_inset

where if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X_{i,j}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim\varphi_{i,j}(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $\{X_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 forms an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{i}$
\end_inset

 glue to a unique sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X_{1},\mathcal{O}_{X_{1}})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(X_{2},\mathcal{O}_{X_{2}})$
\end_inset

 be locally ringed spaces, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1,2}\subset X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2,1}\subset X_{2}$
\end_inset

 be non-empty open subsets, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:(X_{1,2},\mathcal{O}_{X_{1}|X_{1,2}})\to(X_{2,1},\mathcal{O}_{X_{2}|X_{2,1}})$
\end_inset

 be an isomorphism of locally ringed spaces.
 Then we can define a locally ringed space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

, obtained by 
\series bold
gluing 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2,1}$
\end_inset

 via the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As a set, the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is just the disjoint union 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}\coprod X_{2}$
\end_inset

 modulo the equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim f(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X_{1,2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As a topological space, we endow 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with the so-called 
\series bold
quotient topology
\series default
 induced by the above equivalence relation, i.e.
 we say that a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset X$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{1}\subseteq U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{2}\subseteq U_{2}$
\end_inset

 are both open, where 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}=i_{1}(X_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}=i_{2}(X_{2})$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{1}:X_{1}\to X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{2}:X_{2}\to X$
\end_inset

 being the obvious inclusion maps.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As a ringed space, we define the structure sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)=\{(s_{1},s_{2})\mid s_{1}\in\mathcal{O}_{X_{1}}(U\cap X_{1}),\text{ }s_{2}\in\mathcal{O}_{X_{2}}(U\cap X_{2}),\text{ and }f^{*}(s_{2})|{}_{U\cap X_{2,1}}=s_{1}|{}_{U\cap X_{1,2}})\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}=X_{2}=\mathbb{A}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}=U_{2}=\mathbb{A}^{1}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U_{1}\to U_{2}$
\end_inset

 be the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto\frac{1}{x}$
\end_inset

.
 The space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can be thought of as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}\cup\{\infty\}$
\end_inset

.
 Of course the affine line 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}=\mathbb{A}^{1}\subset X$
\end_inset

 sits in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The complement 
\begin_inset Formula $X\backslash X_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a single point that corresponds to the zero point in 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}\cong\mathbb{A}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and hence to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\infty=\frac{1}{0}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the coordinate of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 In the case 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is just the Riemann sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}_{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U_{1}\to U_{2}$
\end_inset

 be the identity map.
 Then the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 obtained by gluing along 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the affine line with the zero point doubled
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Obviously this is a somewhat weird place.
 Speaking in classical terms, if we have a sequence of points tending to
 the zero, this sequence would have two possible limits, namely the two
 zero points.
 Usually we want to exclude such spaces from the objects we consider.
 In the theory of manifolds, this is simply done by requiring that a manifold
 satisfies the so-called 
\series bold
Hausdorff property
\series default
.
 This is obviously not satisfied for our space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be the complex affine curve 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{C}^{2}\mid y^{2}=(x-1)(x-2)(x-3)(x-4)\}.
\]

\end_inset

We can 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

compactify
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by adding two points at infinity, corresponding to the limit as 
\begin_inset Formula $x\to\infty$
\end_inset

 and the two possible values for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 To construct this space rigorously, we construct a prevariety as follows:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If we make the coordinate change 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{x}=\frac{1}{x}$
\end_inset

, the equation of the curve becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y^{2}\widetilde{x}^{4}=(1-\widetilde{x})(1-2\widetilde{x})(1-3\widetilde{x})(1-4\widetilde{x}).
\]

\end_inset

If we make an additional coordinate change 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{y}=\frac{y}{x^{4}}$
\end_inset

, then this becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{y}^{2}=(1-\widetilde{x})(1-2\widetilde{x})(1-3\widetilde{x})(1-4\widetilde{x}).
\]

\end_inset

In these coordinates, we can add our two points at infinity, as they now
 correspond to 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{x}=0$
\end_inset

 (and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{y}=\pm1$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Summarizing, our 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

compactified curve
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is just the prevariety obtained by gluing the two affine varieties
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{C}^{2}\mid y^{2}=(x-1)(x-2)(x-3)(x-4)\}\quad\text{and}\quad\widetilde{X}=\{(\widetilde{x},\widetilde{y})\in\mathbb{C}^{2}\mid\widetilde{y}^{2}=(1-\widetilde{x})(1-2\widetilde{x})(1-3\widetilde{x})(1-4\widetilde{x})\}
\]

\end_inset

along the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f:U\to\widetilde{U},\qquad(x,y)\mapsto(\widetilde{x},\widetilde{y})=\left(\frac{1}{x},\frac{y}{x^{n}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}:\widetilde{U}\to U,\qquad(\widetilde{x},\widetilde{y})\mapsto(x,y)=\left(\frac{1}{\widetilde{x}},\frac{\widetilde{y}}{\widetilde{x}^{n}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\{x\neq0\}\subset X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{U}=\{\widetilde{x}\neq0\}\subset\widetilde{X}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
\end_document
